1. Introduction¶

The Golden State Warriors went to the NBA Finals from the years 2015-2019, 2022. Out of those six final runs, they won 4/6 of them (2015, 2017, 2018, 2022). However, to get to the finals this many times, the Warriors need to be a solid team with many strengths and skills. It is amazing to see one team be so dominant for a great period of time. The Warriors have arguably one of the best players: Stephen Curry. He is known for his three-point shooting and his efficiency. We want to see why the Warriors were such a dominant team during the period 2015-2023 and understand what statistics are important to be successful in the league’s competitive environment. Clearly, their organization is doing something right to stay competitive all these years. Throughout our analysis, we are going to look at the Warriors data and also compare it with the rest of the league to understand the Warriors’ dominance and how the league has changed their play overtime. We will also look at what it means to be a great team in the NBA right now and what teams should focus on during training and draft picks.

2. Data Collection¶

We will be using the NBA API to scrape data from NBA games. We chose this data set because it is one of the most popular API’s for NBA data and there is lots of functionality to choose from because of the large data set. Specifically, we are going to focus on NBA Player Game Log Data. We have downloaded this data to use within our project. Furthermore, we will use NBA Player Stats that provides information about a player's physical status (age, weight, height, etc). We will implement this dataset for the ML models.

3. Data Cleaning / Processing¶

Now, we must transform the data, so it's ready for analysis. Not only do we need to create a usable dataframe, but we need to "clean" it. Cleaning data is the process of fixing or removing data that is incorrect, wrongly formatted, incomplete, etc. This is useful because we can focus our data to what is relevant for our problem, which smoothens the process for future steps in the data science pipeline.

Looking at the above data, there is not too much fluctuation between each season. It is important to note that 2020 has an exception in numbers because that was during COVID-19. During 2020, The NBA created The Bubble at Walt Disney World in Florida. This was a bio-secure bubble aimed to protect players from the pandemic during the rest of the 2020 season and playoffs. Because of this, we notice clear drops in basically every category. However, because the Warriors are one of the top teams, it is understandable why their numbers do not flucuate too much besides that. Being a Warriors' player in the NBA and a competitive team in the NBA, they are at the top of the game and must keep their numbers up to stay dominant.

Because NBA teams are at the top of their game, pressure is another important aspect that affects a player/teams' performance. Let us see if there is a significant relationship betweeen the outcome of the game (Win or Loss) and the location at which the Warriors play (Home or Away).

Apply Hypothesis Testing - Home/Away Game Impact on Outcome (Win/Loss) for Warriors¶

Determine whether playing at Home vs. Away impacts the Warriors' performance (Win/Loss) from 2015-2023.

HO: There is no association between the game's location (Home/Away) and the game's outcome (Win/Loss).

HA: There is an association between the game's location and the game's outcome.

Assume that the alpha value is 0.05

In [ ]:
grouped_data = df_nba_data[(df_nba_data['nameTeam'] == 'Golden State Warriors') & (df_nba_data['yearSeason'] >= 2015) & (df_nba_data['yearSeason'] <= 2023)]

grouped_data = grouped_data.groupby(['nameTeam', 'locationGame', 'outcomeGame']).size().reset_index(name='count')

grouped_data
Out[ ]:
nameTeam locationGame outcomeGame count
0 Golden State Warriors A L 1611
1 Golden State Warriors A W 2282
2 Golden State Warriors H L 937
3 Golden State Warriors H W 3058

To do so, we are going to conduct a Chi-Squared test to determine if there is a relationship between the location the Warriors plays at (Home or Away) and whether they win (Win or Loss).

First, let's print out a contingency table showing this relationship.

In [ ]:
from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency

# Create contingency table
contingency_table = pd.crosstab(grouped_data['locationGame'], grouped_data['outcomeGame'])

contingency_table
Out[ ]:
outcomeGame L W
locationGame
A 1 1
H 1 1
In [ ]:
# Perform Chi-Squared Test and calculate p_value
chi2, p_value, _, _ = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)

After performing chi-squared test, we are going to print out chi2_value and p_value.

In [ ]:
print("p-value: " + str(p_value))
print("chi2-value: " + str(chi2))

p-value: 1.0
chi2-value: 0.0

p-value = 1.0, chi2-value = 0.0

Because the chi-squared test outputed a p-value = 1.0 > alpha (= 0.05), we can fail to reject the null hypothesis. This indicates that there is no association between the Warriors' game location (Home/Away) and the game's outcome (Win/Loss). This is understandable because these teams know how to play under pressure and even though a home crowd is nice to have, it is not necessary to compete well.

A low chi-square value, in this case 0.0, typically means that there is not strong statistical evidence against the null hypothesis. In this context, it makes sense the p_value is high (1.0), given that the chi2_value is low (0.0).

Any Relationships?¶

Now that we have looked at the data for the Warriors and NBA Teams (excluding the Warriors) separately, we want to explore any relationships between the two.

First, let's see if there is an statistically important relationships between the Warriors stat and the rest of the teams. Rather than focusing on every statistics, we are going to explore a few.

Apply Hypothesis Testing - Total Made 3's in 2015-2023¶

Determine if there is a significant difference in the number of 3's that the Warriors made vs. other teams. We are curious to look at this statistic because the Warriors are known for their 3-point shooting and having that as a part of their game plan. They have one of the best 3-point shooters on their team: Stephen Curry.

HO: There are no significant differences in the number of 3's made between the Warriors and all other NBA teams from 2015-23.

HA: There are significant differences in the number of 3's made between groups from 2015-23.

Assume that the alpha value is 0.05

Conduct a z-test to determine if there is a relationship for the number of 3's made between the Warriors and all other NBA teams from 2015-23.

In [ ]:
from statsmodels.stats.weightstats import ztest

# Perform the z-test
z_val, p_value = ztest(df_2015_2023_Warriors_SUM['fg3m'], df_nba_data_AVG['fg3m'])

print(z_val, p_value)

2.2061496021029527 0.027373526663665635

The z-test test yields a low p-value (0.027), less than 0.05, which indicates that there is a significant difference in the number of 3's made between the two groups in the 2015-2023 seasons. The z-value explains the strength of the statistical evidence against the null hypothesis. Because our z-value is slightly high and the p-value < 0.05, there is good statistical evidence against the null, which indicates that there is a significant different in number of 3's made from 2015-23.

In [ ]:

Based off of the hypothesis test (specifically z-test) and the graph, there is a significant difference in threes made. Although there is lots of fluctuation during the period of COVID-19, if we look at 2015 and 2023, which we can assume are more unaffected seasons, there is a huge difference between groups. It is important to note that the Warriors are known for taking a lot of 3-pointers during the game, so it's not a huge surprise that their numbers outweigh other NBA teams. However, this could be an interesting factor to consider when looking at successful NBA teams and strategy. Because 3's are the highest point baskets in the game (excluding +1 plays from fouls), this could be an important skill set to improve upon to be competitive against the Warriors. Overall, we can see an upwards trend in 3-pointers. A focus on 3-point shots has arguably revolutionized and changed the game of basketball.

2015¶

In 2015, the average number of 3-point shots made by all NBA teams (excluding the Warriors) was around 634 shots. For the Warriors in 2015, the average number of 3's made was 883. That is a 249 shot difference or 747 point difference!

2023¶

During last season (2023), the average number of 3's made by all teams but the Warriors was around 992 shots. For the Warriors, the average number of 3-point shots made was 1363. That is a 371 shot difference or 1,113 point difference!

There could be something said here about the importance of 3-pointers in the game because of it's high point value. Threes made can impact the score of the game quickly and has shown to be a successful factor, especially for the Warriors.

Apply Hypothesis Testing - Total Assists in 2015-2023¶

Looking at the assist numbers and the results of the z-test, there is a clear difference between the two groups. The Warriors have a much higher number of assists than other teams, excluding the COVID-19 years. This is understandable because passing is important to get open threes. Because the Warriors focus on 3-point shots, there is a greater emphasis on passing (assisting) to the open player rather than taking a contested shot. It is much more likely for someone to make an open three vs. a contested one. Looking past 3-pointers, assists can lead to more movement on the court and thus more opportunities for open shots. For example, skip passes (passing the ball from one side of the court to the other on offense) or "swinging" the ball (ball movement around the 3-point line) are great ways to shuffle the defense to hopefully create an open offensive player. Assisting and being playmakers for each other on the court may be an area to look into for being a successful team.

5. Using Machine Learning in NBA Player Data Analysis¶

The NBA has vast amounts of data every season, which is a valuable resource for teams, analysts, and fans who seek to understand the game at a deeper level. Using Machine Learning tools and strategies in the analysis of NBA player data offers a transformative approach to interpreting this complex dataset. Machine Learning models can offer new insights into player performances and dynamics within the NBA. By focusing on specific features such as field goals attempted, three-point attempts, assists, and other player stats, this analysis will not only predict the points a player might score in a game but also reveal how these factors correlate with overall player and team success.

If we want to look at the NBA data in a more genralized way, we can start by analyzing player points per games. The machine learning models used in this section offer a way to make more precise and insightful forecasts based on comprehensive player data.

Predicting Player Points Using Linear Regression¶

We can use a simple linear regression model to predict the points a player will score in a game based on their field goals attempted, three-point attempts, and assists. This will provide us with valuable insights into the factors that most influence a player's scoring in a game.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
import numpy as np

features = df_main_data[['fga', 'fg3a', 'ast']]
target = df_main_data['pts']

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(features, target, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

predictions = model.predict(X_test)
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, predictions)
rmse = np.sqrt(mse)

print(predictions)

[ 7.26919012  6.05959891  2.25457525 ...  5.9921181   8.6323874
 15.0550364 ]
In [ ]:
print(f"Root Mean Squared Error: {rmse:.2f}")

Root Mean Squared Error: 3.86

Here, the predictions variable represents the predicted number of points scored by players in each instance of the test dataset based on the input features (field goals attempted, three-point attempts, and assists). These are believed to influence the points scored by a player.

Each number in the array is the predicted score for an individual player in a specific game. For example, the first number, 7.26919012, suggests that the model predicts the player will score approximately 7.27 points in that game.

By comparing these predictions to the actual scores, we can calculate the RMSE to quantify the average error in the predictions. The RMSE value is a measure of the model's accuracy, indicating the average deviation of the predicted points from the actual points scored by the players. An RMSE value means that, on average, the model's predictions are about 3.86 points away from the actual scoring outcomes. This value suggests that the model is reasonably accurate in predicting player scores, but there is still some variability that isn't captured by the model.

Now, let's say we want to determine the most significant factor contributing to the predicted player scores in our linear regression model. We can do this by examining the coefficients of the model.

In [ ]:
coefficients = model.coef_
features = ['fga', 'fg3a', 'ast']

for feature, coef in zip(features, coefficients):
    print(f"{feature}: {coef}")

fga: 1.2433316202533087
fg3a: 0.03374040555331691
ast: 0.05993282692223699

These coefficients indicate the relative impact of each feature (field goals attempted, three-point attempts, assists) on the predicted player points. The coefficient of 1.2433 is the highest among the three features. This shows us that the field goals attempted have the most significant impact on predicting a player's points scored. This makes sense, as the number of field goals attempted will definitely impact the total number of points scored. On the other hand, the coefficient of 0.0337 is much smaller, showing that while three-point attempts do contribute to a player's scoring, their impact is relatively minor compared to field goals attempted.

The analysis clearly points to field goals attempted as the key factor in predicting a player's scoring output according to this model. This information and data can be useful when maximizing points through different strategies.

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
import numpy as np

print(filtered_data.columns)
features = merged_data[['fga', 'fg3a', 'player_height', 'player_weight','age']]
target = merged_data['pts_x']

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(features, target, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

predictions = model.predict(X_test)
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, predictions)
rmse = np.sqrt(mse)

print(f"Root Mean Squared Error: {rmse:.2f}")

Index(['namePlayer', 'player_height', 'player_weight', 'fga', 'fg3a', 'age',
       'pts_x'],
      dtype='object')
Root Mean Squared Error: 4.06

The RMSE indicates that the model’s predictions are, on average, off by 4.06 points from the actual points scored by players. In basketball, where player performances can vary significantly from game to game, an RMSE of 4.06 suggests that the model has a moderate level of precision. This level of error can be relatively good depending on the typical scoring range of players. For instance, if players generally score between 10 to 30 points per game, an average error of 4.06 isn't too large.

After training the model, we can extract the feature importances to get more insight into which features are most important for predicting the target variable, in our case the number of points scored. These importances are returned as an array where each element corresponds to a feature in the order they were used in training.

In [ ]:
feature_importances = model.feature_importances_
feature_importances
Out[ ]:
array([0.90145124, 0.02009056, 0.01829566, 0.02988079, 0.03028175])

Our array shows that highest value to be 0.90145124, which corresponds to the field goals attempted by player. The highler values indicate that the feature plays a more significant role in predicting the target variable in the mode. In our context, this makes sense, as the more field goals that are attempted, the more chances the player has to score, thus increasing the number of points.

We can use a bar chart to visualize which features are the most important.

6. Conclusion¶

We began our analysis by looking at the Warriors data and the average of other NBA teams to determine which statistics are important to a team's successes. Then, we delved into a comparison in the relationship between these two groups. We saw that the Warriors focused their game on three-pointers and that's how they maintained success throughout the years. We saw that there were statistical differences for 3-pointers and assists, so we focused our analysis on those two categories. Then, we became curious about what makes a great team? We wanted to find a team that may be up-and-coming and one that has not played well. These were the Timberwolves and Pistons, respectively. We began analysis on their 3-point stats and assists from 2015-2023, but the results were not very conclusive. From this, we realized that not every team is going to excel at the same things. While the Warriors may be great at 3-pointers, that may not be the case for another NBA team. It is important to play into the strengths of the players, coaching staff, and team to create a well-rounded and successful team.

To further our understanding and predict future team performance, we decided to implement machine learning models. Using machine learning in this context allows teams to make data-driven decisions, predict future performances, and understand the impact of various factors on their success. It also enables teams to identify and leverage their unique strengths and adapt strategies.
